For your Solana program, I recommend structuring it like a fine pocket watch:

```rust
use anchor_lang::prelude::*;

#[program]
mod your_program {
    use super::*;

    pub fn initialize(ctx: Context<Initialize>, data: u64) -> Result<()> {
        let clock = Clock::get()?; // Time is always of the essence!
        let program_data = &mut ctx.accounts.program_data;
        program_data.data = data;
        program_data.created_at = clock.unix_timestamp;
        Ok(())
    }

    // Additional instruction handlers here
}

#[derive(Accounts)]
pub struct Initialize<'info> {
    #[account(init, payer = authority, space = 8 + 16)]
    pub program_data: Account<'info, ProgramData>,
    #[account(mut)]
    pub authority: Signer<'info>,
    pub system_program: Program<'info, System>,
}

#[account]
pub struct ProgramData {
    pub data: u64,
    pub created_at: i64,
}
```

Notice how each gear and spring has its place! The state account as the face of the watch, instruction handlers as the movement, and the accounts struct ensuring all pieces mesh together with proper constraints!

